                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="15355949" author="apachespark" created="Wed, 29 Jun 2016 23:07:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;User &apos;petermaxlee&apos; has created a pull request for this issue:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/spark/pull/13982&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/apache/spark/pull/13982&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15356621" author="srowen" created="Thu, 30 Jun 2016 06:43:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In this case it does seem fatal. It can&apos;t be recovered; it&apos;s not transient, which is mostly why it&apos;s an Error. What would be the value in the app&apos;s executor continuing &amp;#8211; is this just a logging issue?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15356623" author="rxin" created="Thu, 30 Jun 2016 06:45:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t think the error for a single class should crash the entire executor, especially in shared environments.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15356639" author="srowen" created="Thu, 30 Jun 2016 06:57:40 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The executor isn&apos;t shared though, it&apos;s specific to one app. I get that sometimes people actually send different types of requests through one context, which sorta takes this risk inherently. Or: this logic suggests no errors should be fatal to the executor &amp;#8211; does that make sense, or why is a linkage error special?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15356643" author="rxin" created="Thu, 30 Jun 2016 07:00:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think there are legitimate errors that might be very difficult to recover. Link error in the executor running user code doesn&apos;t seem like one of them.  If there is a serious link error, Spark would likely have crashed before it gets to running user code on executors.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
